Interview Questions
1. What is the this keyword in java? What is the main purpose of this in a class?
-->this is a reference variable in Java that refers to the current object (the object whose method or constructor is being executed).
    
    👉 Main purpose:
    To access the current object's properties and methods.
    
    class Student {
        int id;
    
        void display() {
            System.out.println(this.id); // refers to current object
        }
    }


2. How is this used to refer to current object?
-->Inside a class method or constructor, this automatically points to the current object.
    In Java, the this keyword is a reference variable that points to the current object—the specific instance whose method or constructor is
        currently being executed.
    Differentiating Instance Variables from Parameters: The most common use is to resolve naming conflicts (shadowing) when a method parameter
      has the same name as a class field.
    Example: this.name = name; assigns the local parameter name to the current object's field name.
    Invoking Current Class Constructors (this()): Used for constructor chaining to call one constructor from another within the same class.
    Note: The call to this() must be the very first statement in the constructor.

class Test {
    void show() {
        System.out.println(this); // prints current object reference
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t = new Test();
        t.show();
    }
}



3. How can this be used to differentiate instance variables from local variables?
-->When local variables and instance variables have the same name, this is used to avoid confusion.
    
    class Student {
        int id;
    
        Student(int id) {
            this.id = id; // instance = local
        }
    }
    👉 Without this, Java gets confused between local variable and instance variable



4. How is this used to call another constructor in the same class? (this() constructor chaining).
-->this() is used to call another constructor in the same class.

    class Demo {
        Demo() {
            System.out.println("Default constructor");
        }
    
        Demo(int x) {
            this(); // calling default constructor
            System.out.println("Parameterized constructor");
        }
    }
    
    ⚠️ Important rules:
    
    Must be first statement in constructor
    Used for code reuse



5. Can this be used in a static method? Why or why not?
-->❌ No

  👉 Reason:
  this refers to an object, but static methods belong to the class, not objects.
  
  static void show() {
      // System.out.println(this); ❌ ERROR
  }


6. Can this be passed as an argument to a method or constructor? Give an example.
-->✅ Yes

    👉 You can pass current object as parameter.
    
    class Test {
        void display(Test obj) {
            System.out.println("Method called");
        }
    
        void show() {
            display(this); // passing current object
        }
    }


7. How does this help in method chaining?
-->Method chaining means calling multiple methods in a single statement.

👉 this returns current object → allows chaining

class Demo {
    Demo show() {
        System.out.println("Show");
        return this;
    }

    Demo display() {
        System.out.println("Display");
        return this;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Demo().show().display();
    }
}
✅ Final Output:
Show
Display


8. Difference between this and current class name for object reference.
-->
| Feature         | `this`                  | Class Name            |
| --------------- | ----------------------- | --------------------- |
| Refers to       | Current object          | Class itself          |
| Usage           | Inside instance methods | Static context        |
| Example         | `this.id`               | `ClassName.staticVar` |
| Object Required | Yes                     | No                    |

class Demo {
    int x;
    static int y;

    void show() {
        System.out.println(this.x); // instance
        System.out.println(Demo.y); // static
    }
}




If interviewer asks:
👉 "Why do we need this keyword?"

You can say:
-->
"this is used to refer to the current object, resolve variable ambiguity, enable constructor chaining, pass the current object,
and support method chaining."
